Conditionals.

The basic conditional in the shell is the if structure: if some command succeeds, then run one block; optionally, else-if another command succeeds, run a second block; otherwise run a final block; and the whole thing is closed with f-i, which is if spelled backwards. The crucial insight is that the condition is any command at all, and what counts as true is its exit code. An exit code of zero means success, which the shell treats as true, and any non-zero code means failure, treated as false. So writing if, then a command, runs the body whenever that command succeeds.

Most conditions, though, are tests about files and strings, and these use the test command, which comes in three equivalent forms. There is the word test itself, the single square brackets which are the posix alias for it, and the double square brackets which are the modern bash form. All three answer questions like, is this a regular file? The double-bracket form is the one to prefer in bash, because it behaves the same but adds conveniences: you can use and-and and or-or inside it, do regular-expression matching, and you do not have to quote your variables as carefully.

There is a set of test operators worth memorising. For files, dash e asks whether something exists, dash f whether it is a regular file, dash d whether it is a directory, dash r, dash w, and dash x whether it is readable, writable, or executable, and dash s whether it exists and is non-empty. For numbers, there are operators like greater-than and less-than spelled out as dash g-t and dash l-t. And for strings, dash z is true when a string is empty, dash n when it is non-empty, and you can compare two strings for equality, or, with the double brackets, match one against a regular expression. Those few operators cover the vast majority of real conditions you will ever write.
